        image: registry.k8s.io/nginx-slim:0.24

---


This is priority strength (1–100)
Weight defines priority; higher weight = more preferred
Each matching rule adds weight
Node with highest total weight wins

| Node  | Matches rule? | Weight |
| ----- | ------------- | ------ |
| node1 | yes           | 100    |
| node2 | yes           | 50     |
| node3 | no            | 0      |


More Info: https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/openshift_container_platform/4.18/html/operator_apis/config-imageregistry-operator-openshift-io-v1

# Anti Affinity

spec:
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
    spec:
      affinity:
        podAntiAffinity:
          requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
          - labelSelector:
              matchExpressions:
              - key: app
                operator: In
                values:
                - myapp
            topologyKey: kubernetes.io/hostname


Node selector
Pod chooses node by label.
Simple and exact.

Affinity / anti-affinity
Pod expresses rules or preferences.
More advanced and smarter.

Taints / tolerations
Node blocks pods unless they are allowed.
Best for isolation and reservation.


====================

Taints and Tolerations

===
LAB 1 — TAINTS & TOLERATIONS (Hands-on)

Goal
Control where pods are scheduled.

Step 1: Check your nodes
oc get nodes --show-labels

Step 2: Add a taint to a node

Pick one worker node (example):
oc adm taint nodes ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal key=infra:NoSchedule

Meaning:
No pod can schedule here
Unless it has matching toleration

Verify taint
oc describe node ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal | grep Taints

Step 3: Create a pod WITHOUT toleration
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: test-no-toleration
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
oc apply -f pod.yaml

Result:
oc get pod

Status: Pending

Reason:
oc describe pod test-no-toleration

You’ll see:
node(s) had taint {key=infra: NoSchedule}

Step 4: Add toleration (FIX)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: test-with-toleration
spec:
  tolerations:
  - key: "key"
    operator: "Equal"
    value: "infra"
    effect: "NoSchedule"
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx

oc apply -f pod.yaml


Concept	Meaning
Taint	Node says “don’t come here”
Toleration	Pod says “I can handle it”

===

LAB 2 — INFRA NODE (VERY IMPORTANT in OpenShift)

What is Infra Node?

Dedicated node for:

Router pods (ingress)
Registry
Monitoring
Logging

Keeps app workloads separate

Step 1: Label node as infra
oc label node ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal node-role.kubernetes.io/infra=""

Step 2: Add taint (IMPORTANT)
oc adm taint nodes ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal node-role.kubernetes.io/infra=true:NoSchedule

Step 3: Move router to infra node
oc patch ingresscontroller.operator default \
  -n openshift-ingress-operator \
  --type=merge \
  -p '{
    "spec": {
      "nodePlacement": {
        "nodeSelector": {
          "matchLabels": {
            "node-role.kubernetes.io/infra": ""
          }
        },
        "tolerations": [
          {
            "key": "node-role.kubernetes.io/infra",
            "operator": "Exists",
            "effect": "NoSchedule"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }'

Verify
oc get pods -n openshift-ingress -o wide

Router pods should move to infra node ✅

Node Type	Purpose
Worker	Application pods
Infra	Platform services
Master	Control plane

===

LAB 3 — DISABLING A NODE

Scenario:
Maintenance / issue / upgrade

Step 1: Cordon node (disable scheduling)
oc adm cordon ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal

Node still running pods
But no new pods

Step 2: Drain node (evacuate pods)
oc adm drain ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data

Moves pods to other nodes

Verify
oc get pods -o wide

Step 3: Uncordon (enable back)
oc adm uncordon ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal

===

Important Notes (REAL WORLD)
Action	Impact
cordon	safe
drain	disruptive
taint	permanent control

Difference:

Feature	Use
Node Selector	Simple placement
Affinity	Advanced rules
Taint	Block scheduling
Toleration	Allow exception



